<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,330,1402]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,303,330,356]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Description.</emphasis>
Imago (
<figureCitation box="[407,498,330,356]" captionStart="FIGURES 51 – 58" captionStartId="22.[151,269,1371,1395]" captionTargetBox="[332,1255,194,1347]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[332,1255,194,1347]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 51 – 58. Imagos. 51. Agnippe crinella. 52, Agnippe prunifoliella. 53, Glauce pectenalaeella. 54, Telphusa longifasciella. 55, Arogalea cristifasciella. 56, Sinoe robiniella. 57, Recurvaria nanella. 58, Exoteleia dodecella." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/182960/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Fig. 
<number box="[465,498,330,356]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="55.0">55</number>
</figureCitation>
). Labial palpus with second segment rough-scaled ventrally, third segment as long as second, apex acute. Antenna more than half forewing length. Clypeus with ventral margin rounded. Posterior area of sitophore with four campaniform sensilla in line except left side; anterior area with seven campaniform sensilla. Ocellus present. Forewing (length/width ratio 
<number box="[958,996,450,476]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="4.3">4.3</number>
) with slight tufts of raised scales easily lost and sometimes absent in worn specimens; R 
<number box="[759,767,506,520]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="5.0">5</number>
, M 
<number box="[808,816,506,520]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1.0">1</number>
, M 
<number box="[857,865,506,520]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2.0">2</number>
, and M 
<number box="[955,963,506,520]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="3.0">3</number>
separated, CuA 
<number box="[1151,1159,506,520]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1.0">1</number>
and CuA 
<number box="[1272,1280,506,520]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2.0">2</number>
present (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 18" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[177,1432,444,1782]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[166,1443,434,1793]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 18. Wing venation. 7 – 14, Forewing. 7, Sinoe robiniella. ps = pterostigma. 8, Carpatolechia sp. 1. 9, Arogalea cristifasciella. 10, Agnippe sp. 1. 11, Stenolechia gemmella. 12, Parastenolechia nigrinotella. 13, Parachronistis albiceps. 14, Arcutelphusa talladega, sp. nov., 15 – 18, Hindwing. 15, Agnippe sp. 1. 16, Sinoe robiniella. 17, Arogalea cristifasciella. 18, Arcutelphusa talladega, sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/182951/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,168,533,559]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
); subbasal fascia directed from apex of costa toward posterior margin. Hindwing (length/width ratio 
<number box="[1389,1427,533,559]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="3.9">3.9</number>
) with R 
<number box="[230,238,589,603]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="5.0">5</number>
and M 
<number box="[321,329,589,603]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1.0">1</number>
well separated, M 
<number box="[546,554,589,603]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="3.0">3</number>
and CuA 
<number box="[666,674,589,603]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1.0">1</number>
separated (
<figureCitation box="[808,895,573,599]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 18" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[177,1432,444,1782]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[166,1443,434,1793]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 18. Wing venation. 7 – 14, Forewing. 7, Sinoe robiniella. ps = pterostigma. 8, Carpatolechia sp. 1. 9, Arogalea cristifasciella. 10, Agnippe sp. 1. 11, Stenolechia gemmella. 12, Parastenolechia nigrinotella. 13, Parachronistis albiceps. 14, Arcutelphusa talladega, sp. nov., 15 – 18, Hindwing. 15, Agnippe sp. 1. 16, Sinoe robiniella. 17, Arogalea cristifasciella. 18, Arcutelphusa talladega, sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/182951/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Fig. 
<number box="[863,895,573,599]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
). Male abdominal tergum VIII subrectangular (
<figureCitation box="[159,247,616,642]" captionStart="FIGURES 19 – 24" captionStartId="10.[151,269,1239,1263]" captionTargetBox="[319,1268,326,1199]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[308,1279,323,1213]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 19 – 24. Characters of the labial palpi and abdomen. 19 – 20, Third segment of labial palpus. 19, Recurvaria leucatella. 20, Istrianis myricariella. 21 - 22, Male sternum VIII. Telphusa perspicua. 21, Arcutelphusa talladega sp. nov., 22. Coleotechnites sp. 1, 23 – 24. Male tergum VIII. 23, Teleiopsis diffinis. ahp = anterolateral hair pencil. 24, Arogalea cristifasciella." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/182952/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Fig. 
<number box="[214,247,616,642]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="24.0">24</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,330,1402]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[384,475,656,682]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 – 29" captionStartId="12.[151,269,1892,1916]" captionTargetBox="[213,1360,320,1854]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[201,1386,320,1869]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 25 – 29. Male genitalia, basal articulation (ba), dorsal gnathos (dg), ventral gnathos (vg), and uncus (u). 25, Agnippe sp. 1. 26, Glauce sp. 1. 27, Arogalea cristifasciella. 28, Telphusa sedulitella. a, tegumen. b, vinculum and phallus. 29, Sinoe robiniella. a, tegumen. b, phallus. c, vinculum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/182953/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Fig. 
<number box="[441,475,656,682]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="27.0">27</number>
</figureCitation>
): uncus hoodlike, apically rounded, subequal in length with gnathos; ventral part of gnathos cushionlike, trilobed at apex, without basal articulation, dorsal part absent; valva with costal part sinuous, with bulbous base; posterolateral margins of vinculum well developed, symmetrical; tegumen narrower mesially than basally, basal width/length ratio 
<number box="[775,815,776,802]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="0.3">0.3</number>
; phallus as long as length of tegumen, straight, slen- der, with transverse, sclerotized band on ventral surface at base, without cornuti.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,330,1402]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[414,506,856,882]" captionStart="FIGURE 44 – 46" captionStartId="17.[151,255,2008,2032]" captionTargetBox="[218,1352,666,1962]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[211,1376,656,1982]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 44 – 46. Female genitalia. 44, Glauce sp. 1. 45, Arogalea cristifasciella. 46, Telphusa sedulitella." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/182957/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Fig. 
<number box="[472,506,856,882]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="45.0">45</number>
</figureCitation>
): apophyses posteriores about 
<date box="[878,918,856,882]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<number box="[878,893,856,882]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2.0">2</number>
x
</date>
length of apophyses anteriores; apophyses anteriores about 
<number box="[349,393,896,922]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">
1– 
<date box="[377,393,896,922]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">2</date>
</number>
x length of abdominal segment VIII; antrum sclerotized, cylindrical, width subequal to length of ductus bursae; ductus bursae covered with spinules, with colliculum; signum a small plate supporting a digitate process.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,330,1402]" box="[197,436,1016,1042]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Larva. Undescribed.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,330,1402]" box="[197,427,1056,1082]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Pupa. Undescribed.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,330,1402]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,325,1096,1122]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[336,444,1096,1121]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Arogalea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[336,444,1096,1121]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Arogalea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is superficially similar to the European genera 
<emphasis box="[1029,1382,1096,1121]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<taxonomicName box="[1029,1168,1096,1121]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Stenolechia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Stenolechia</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1183,1378,1096,1121]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Parastenolechia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Parastenolechia</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[151,326,1136,1161]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Stenolechiodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,326,1136,1161]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Stenolechiodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the one known species, 
<emphasis box="[753,954,1136,1161]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<taxonomicName box="[753,950,1136,1161]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Gelechia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cristifasciella">A. cristifasciella</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
differs from other species in having the trilobed apex of the gnathos in male genitalia. 
<taxonomicName box="[692,800,1176,1201]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Arogalea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[692,800,1176,1201]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Arogalea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[856,1197,1176,1201]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Pseudotelphusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basifasciella">
<emphasis box="[856,1197,1176,1201]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Pseudotelphusa basifasciella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differ from all other Nearctic Teleiodini in having forewings with white ground color, but the latter species differs in having the subbasal fascia extending from the wing base toward the posterior margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,330,1402]" box="[197,1238,1296,1322]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,274,1296,1322]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Hosts.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[282,396,1296,1322]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fagaceae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName box="[407,505,1296,1321]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[407,505,1296,1321]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Quercus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. (
<bibRefCitation author="Forbes" box="[575,726,1296,1322]" pageId="18" pageNumber="43" refString="Forbes, W. T. M. (1923) Lepidoptera of New York and neighboring states. Part I. Primitive forms, microlepidoptera, pyraloids, bombyces. Memoirs Cornell University Agricultural Experiment Station 68: 1 - 729." type="journal article" year="1923">
Forbes 
<number box="[664,726,1296,1322]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1923.0">1923</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Robinson" box="[738,986,1296,1322]" pageId="18" pageNumber="47" refString="Robinson, G. S., Ackery, P. R., Kitching, I. J., Beccaloni, G. W., and Hernandez, L. M. (2002) Hostplants of the moth and butterfly caterpillars of America north of Mexico. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute 69: 1 - 824." type="journal article" year="2002">
Robinson 
<emphasis box="[858,916,1296,1321]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[924,986,1296,1322]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Wagner" box="[998,1225,1296,1322]" pageId="18" pageNumber="47" refString="Wagner, D. L., Peacock, J. W., Carter, J. L., and Talley, S. E. (1995) Spring caterpillar fauna of oak and blueberry in a Virginia deciduous forest. Annals of the Entomological Society of America 88: 416 - 426." type="journal article" year="1995">
Wagner 
